 <h2>Fundamental Analysis</h2>

<p>
Fundamental analysis focuses on understanding the business behind a stock.
Instead of charts, it evaluates a company’s financial health, performance,
and long-term potential.
</p>

<p>
Investors using fundamental analysis aim to identify companies that are
strong, sustainable, and undervalued by the market.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Financial Statements:</strong>
    Analyzing income statements, balance sheets, and cash flows
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Key Ratios:</strong>
    Metrics like P/E ratio, ROE, and debt levels to assess company strength
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Business Model:</strong>
    Understanding how a company makes money and sustains growth
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Economic & Industry Factors:</strong>
    Impact of interest rates, inflation, and sector trends
  </li>
</ul>

<p>
Fundamental analysis is commonly used for long-term investing,
where patience and conviction matter more than short-term price movements.
</p>

<p class="text-muted">
In the long run, stock prices reflect business performance.
</p>

