    <h2>IPO Investing</h2>

<p>
An Initial Public Offering (IPO) is the process through which a private company
offers its shares to the public for the first time and gets listed on the stock market.
</p>

<p>
IPOs allow retail investors to participate early in a company’s journey,
but they also come with uncertainty and limited historical data.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <strong>Why Companies Go Public:</strong>
    To raise capital, expand operations, or provide exits to early investors
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Subscription Categories:</strong>
    Retail, HNI, and Qualified Institutional Buyers (QIB)
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Pricing & Demand:</strong>
    Issue price, subscription levels, and market sentiment
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Listing Day vs Long-Term:</strong>
    Short-term excitement versus business fundamentals
  </li>
</ul>

<p>
IPO investing requires careful evaluation, not just excitement.
Understanding the business, risks, and valuation is essential before applying.
</p>

<p class="text-muted">
Not every IPO creates wealth — discipline matters more than demand.
</p>

